revision.text:
'''Documentary comedy''' is a form of [[comedy]]. The comic material used is presented in documentary style—usually, a report on a particular theme or issue—and with the same investigation and reporting methods used to gather the material.

Well-known documentary comics include [[Dave Gorman]],<ref name=gormano>{{cite web|title=Live|url=http://gormano.blogspot.co.uk/2008/10/live.html|publisher=gormano.blogspot.co.uk|accessdate=1 September 2012|date=28 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=comedy>{{cite web|title=Dave Gorman's Googlewhack Adventure|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/dave_gorman_googlewhack/|publisher=comedy.co.uk|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> [[Danny Wallace (humourist)|Danny Wallace]], [[Tony Hawks]], [[Alex Horne]]<ref name="telegraph">{{cite news|title=Why it’s time for horseback cricket to make a comeback|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/7907491/Why-its-time-for-horseback-cricket-to-make-a-comeback.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=23 July 2010}}</ref> and [[Mark Steel]].

It is not to be confused with [[mockumentary]], a form of [[parody|spoof]] in which a documentary is played "straight" but based on fictitious material.

