The use of '''[[radio]]s in [[Bahrain]]''' extend as far back as to 1940 when the country's first radio broadcasting station was opened by the British.<ref name="frishkopf"/> In 1955, the country's first radio broadcasting service, in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], first started.<ref name="Wells"/> By 1980, the radio service broadcast up to 14 hours a day. The country's first [[English language]] radio station was later established in 1977, as a result of an increase in English speakers in Bahrain and the [[Persian Gulf]] region.<ref name="Wells">{{cite book|last=Wells|first=Alan|title=World Broadcasting: A Comparative View|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9781567502459|pages=136|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgptYdAcsOgC&pg=PA136 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Radio Bahrain|url=http://www.radiobahrain.fm/index.php?pr=About_Radio_Bahrain|publisher=Radio Bahrain|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> The radio's programmes were primarily religious and educational, with occasional news announcements.<ref name="Wells"/>
Almost all radio stations in Bahrain are state-owned, by the [[Bahrain Radio and Television Corporation]] though privately owned radio stations like the [[Hindi]] / [[Malayalam]] language Radio Mrichi 104.2FM<ref>{{cite news|title=Radio Mirchi to launch in Bahrain|url=https://ultra.news/s-k/39036/radio-mirchi-to-launch-in-bahrain|publisher=Ultra News|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>, which serves the country's [[Indian people|Indian]] community, operate in the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Media|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-14541053|work=Bahrain profile|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>
==History== The British established the Bahrain Broadcasting Station in November 1940 in response to the initiation of pro-[[Nazi]] programmes being broadcast in Arabic in the Persian Gulf from 1934 to 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qdl.qa/en/nazi-propaganda-sharjah-during-world-war-ii|title=NAZI PROPAGANDA IN SHARJAH DURING WORLD WAR II|publisher=qdl.qa|accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> One of the earliest studies done on radio use in Bahrain assert that in 1940, there were 511 radio receivers in operation.<ref name="frishkopf"/> However, radio ownership was not common among the residents, and most people went to cafés to listen to broadcasts. The station was staffed mostly with Bahrainis and its broadcasts included Quranic recitations, the national anthems of Kuwait and Bahrain, and poetry recitations, which may have been in the form of music. The station was closed down in 1945.<ref name="frishkopf">{{cite book|last1=Frishkopf|first1=Michael|title=Music and Media in the Arab World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KANOAYzkhA8C|publisher=The American University in Cairo Press|year=2010|pages=116–117|isbn=978-9774162930}}</ref>
==List== * 93.3FM Bahrain FM (Arabic) * 95.0FM Traditional FM (Bahraini Traditional Music) * 96.5FM Radio Bahrain (English) * 96.9FM Arabic Classic Music Station (Arabic Oldies Music) * 98.4FM Youth Radio (Modern Music) * 102.3FM Bahrain Radio (Arabic) * 104.2FM Radio Mirchi Bahrain (Hindi, Malayalam) * 106.1FM Holy Quran Radio (Religious) * 106.3FM American Base Radio
