'''The Invisible Circus''' is a group of [[Circus|circus performers]] from [[Bristol]] and [[London]] in the United Kingdom.
==Origins== The Invisible Circus is a collective of multi-skilled artists formed during a decade and a half of world travel and adventure as street performers.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
They have appeared in over 20 countries around the world since forming in 1992.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}} Specializing in site-specific performance and made-to-order spectacles, they have performed at events such as the [[Glastonbury Festival of Contemporary Performing Arts]],<ref name="E festivals">{{Cite web | title = Line up - Glastonbury Festival 2008 | publisher = eFestivals | date = 24 June 2008 | accessdate = 2009-08-01 | url = http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/glastonbury/2008/theatre.shtml }}</ref> [[Burning Man]] in the USA, and [[World of Music, Arts and Dance|Womad]] in New Zealand.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==Artspace Lifespace== The Invisible Circus supports and is supported by Artspace Lifespace. The sister [[cooperative]] works in partnership with property managers in order to secure and convert interesting, unusual and often semi-derelict spaces into art venues.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Bristol artists Artspace Lifespace find home in Bridewell | publisher = This Is Bristol | date = 4 November 2008 | accessdate = 2009-08-01 | url = http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/unlikely-home-Bristol-artists-Artspace-Lifespace/article-450013-detail/article.html }}</ref>
==Recent work== In 2007, the Invisible Circus managed and ran the disused [[Pro-Cathedral of the Holy Apostles]] in [[Clifton, Bristol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cathedralapartments.co.uk/|title=Developer's website that includes information on program|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129104024/http://www.cathedralapartments.co.uk/|archivedate=2009-11-29|df=}}</ref> They ran a 12-week series of performances events called ''Revelations''. For their work in the cathedral, the Invisible Circus won the [[Venue (magazine)|Venue]] magazine's Top Banana award in January 2008.<ref>''Venue Magazine'', Bristol News & Media, Jan 2008, p. 10.</ref>
They headlined the big top at the [[Glastonbury Festival 2008]].<ref name="E festivals"/>
In early 2008 they took over the Bridewell police station in the centre of Bristol.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Bridewell police station to become arts venue circus | publisher = This Is Bristol | date = 29 April 2009 | accessdate = 2009-08-01 | url = http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/wdp/news/Bristol-police-station-arts-venue/article-945773-detail/article.html }}</ref> The circus have performed their widely acclaimed, site-specific show ''Carny-Ville'' twice since opening the space.<ref>{{Cite web | publisher = The British Theatre Guide | title = Reviews - Carny-Ville (Almeida) | year = 2007 | author = Lucy Ribchester | accessdate = 2009-08-01 | url = http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/carnyville-rev.htm }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Performance Review - Carny-Ville | publisher = Suit Yourself Magazine | year = 2009 | accessdate = 2009-08-01 | url = http://www.suityourselfmagazine.co.uk/performance-review-carny-ville/ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Carny Ville - The Island | publisher = Crackerjack Bristol | date = 4 May 2009 | author = Martin Booth | accessdate = 2009-08-01 | url = http://www.crackerjack.co.uk/bristol/review/carny-ville-island/community-event }}</ref>
The Invisible Circus have also performed their show ''Combustion Club'' at the Bridewell venue.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Theatre Bristol - What's On - 2009 - 7 - 10 - The Invisible Circus Combustion Club |accessdate=2009-08-01 |url=http://theatrebristol.net/whats-on/2009/7/10/the-invisible-circus-combustion-club |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006213534/http://theatrebristol.net/whats-on/2009/7/10/the-invisible-circus-combustion-club |archivedate=October 6, 2011 }}</ref>
